Figure 1. (a) The growth-per-cycle (GPC, solid squares) and roughness (open circles) of the $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ thin films as a function of the deposition temperature, (b) and (c) the GPC as a function of the LiHMDS (solid squares) and $\mathrm{HQ}$ (open circles) pulse lengths determined at 120 and $220{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, respectively, (d) the $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ film thickness as a function of number of ALD/MLD cycles determined at deposition temperature of $120^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$.

i.e. dilithium 1,4-benzenediolate $\left(\mathrm{Li}_{2}\left[p-\mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{4} \mathrm{O}_{2}\right]\right.$, hereafter $\left.\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{Q}\right)$. Also importantly, no signs of $\mathrm{LiOH}$ or $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}$ were detected either.

The as-deposited $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ thin films were crystalline at all deposition temperatures as verified by grazing incidence $X$-ray diffraction (GIXRD) (Figure S1, ESI). With increasing deposition temperature, a change in the GIXRD patterns can be observed: the peak at $11.5^{\circ}$ diminishes, while a new peak appears at $23.3^{\circ}$. The density of the films, as determined by $X R R$, however stays rather constant at $1.2 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{cm}^{3}$. More detailed diffraction patterns were measured from ca. $800 \mathrm{~nm}$ thick samples deposited at 105 and $220^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$. At the low-temperature end, a well-defined pattern could be obtained (Figure 2a), whereas the high-temperature sample yielded only a few reflections which partially overlapped with those of the low-temperature sample (Figure S2, ESI). Importantly, once formed, the low-temperature sample retains its crystal structure even at elevated temperatures as was investigated through a post-deposition heat treatment at $250^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ in vacuum.

To the best of our knowledge, no prior reports exist on the crystal structure of $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ or related $\mathrm{Li}$-based compounds. However, in bulk samples $\mathrm{HQ}$ is known to form crystalline structures with $\mathrm{Ti}^{[21]}$ and alkali metals ${ }^{[22]}$ other than Li. Most importantly, $\mathrm{Na}_{2}[p$ $\left.\mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{4} \mathrm{O}_{2}\right]$ and $\mathrm{K}_{2}\left[p-\mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{4} \mathrm{O}_{2}\right]$ (hereafter $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ and $\mathrm{K}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$, respectively) are reported to be isostructural. Thus by assuming that $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ would share the same structural motif, the atomic-level structure of the corresponding $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ compound was predicted using density functional theory (PBEO/TZVP, computational details are described in full detail in the ESI). ${ }^{[23-29]}$

Initial optimization of $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ using the space group $\mathrm{P}_{2} / \mathrm{ncm}$ and atomic positions from the $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ data of Couhorn and Dronskowski[22] ended up in a transition state characterized by a single imaginary frequency $\left(64 i \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}\right)$. Changing the geometry in the direction of the normal modes of the imaginary frequency reduced the symmetry to the orthorhombic subgroup $P c c n$, and the subsequent optimization resulted in a true local minimum accompanied with a total energy reduction of $9 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$ per unit cell. The calculated structural parameters are listed in Table S2 in ESI. The structure, shown in the inset of Figure $2 \mathrm{a}$, is still closely similar to that of $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ and $\mathrm{K}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$, and the predicted lattice parameters are: $a=11.49 \AA, b=10.38 \AA, c=4.74 \AA$. In this structure, infinite $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{2}$ pillars running along the c-axis are interconnected by the bidentate $\mathrm{C}_{6} \mathrm{H}_{4} \mathrm{O}_{2}{ }^{2-}$ units with each $\mathrm{Li}$ atom coordinated to three oxygen atoms (Figure S3, ESI). The length of the c-axis for our $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ falls perfectly in line with those reported for the $\mathrm{Na}$ and $\mathrm{K}$ analogues when these values are plotted against the ionic radius of the alkali metal (Figure S4, ESI). On the contrary, the $a$ and $b$ lattice parameters are comparatively larger; this is because in $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ and $\mathrm{K}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ the benzene ring lies more parallel in respect to the $\mathrm{M}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{2}$ chain. In the case of $\mathrm{Li}_{2} \mathrm{Q}$ the shorter Li-O bonds lead to a less distorted chain and consequently, the $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{O}$ bond in the oxygen tetrahedron points to a more outwards\\
